Let’s take this piece of code. What will be the output of the above code?

#include<stdio.h>

int main() {

    int x = 50;

    if (x > 0)

        printf(“x > 0 \n”);

    if (x <= 50)

        printf(“x <= 50 \n”);

    if (x >= 50)

        printf(“x >= 50 \n”);

    if (x > 50)

        printf(“x > 50 \n”);

    return 0;

}

The output will be 

 x > 0  // first if condition is true

 x <= 50 // second if condition also true 

 x >= 50 // third if condition is also true.

But the fourth if condition is false so it will not be printed.

Let’s consider a problem in which you have given n1 = 2, n2 = 3, n3 = 5, and a number x. You need to count how many numbers from n1, n2 and n3 divide x.

Pseudo code:-

#include<stdio.h>

int main() {

    int n1 = 2, n2 = 3, n3 = 5;

    int x;

    int count = 0;

    scanf(“%d”, &x);

    if (x % n1 == 0)

        count++;

    if (x % n2 == 0)

        count++;

    if (x % n3 == 0)

        count++;

    printf(“%d”, Count);

    return 0;

}

If you need to write multiple statements inside the if condition, you have to use curly braces.

Eg. 

if(x % n3 == 0)

{

    count++;

    printf(“x is divisible by n3 \n”);

}




